{"title_page": "Per Welinder", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Per Welinder\n| image         = Per_Welinder.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = Per Welinder's identity badge in 2016\n| caption       = Welinder in 2016.\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    ={{Birth date and age|1962|04|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Sweden]]\n| occupation    = [[entrepreneur]], [[venture capitalist]], [[brand builder]], [[motivational speaker]], [[professional skateboarder]]\n| salary        =\n| networth      =\n| spouse        =\n| children      =\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = {{URL|twitter.com/perwelinder}}\n| alma_mater    = [[UCLA]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])\n| home_town     = [[T\u00e4by]] Sweden\n| net_worth     = \n| known_for     = CEO of [[Blitz Distribution]]; Board Director of [[International Association of Skateboard Companies]]\n}}\n'''Per Nils Welinder''' (born April 17, 1962) is an entrepreneur and a former professional skateboarder. During the 1980s he achieved international fame as a freestyle skater and was a leading member of the elite [[Powell-Peralta]] skate team known as the [[Bones Brigade]]. He had a number of influential video parts with Powell during the 1980s, a series of signature models, and roles in several Hollywood movies. Welinder also has the unique distinction of being the only person to have ever beaten [[Rodney Mullen]] in a professional skate contest.\n\n==Biography==\nWelinder was born in T\u00e4by, just outside [[Stockholm]].  In the 1980s, Welinder and Mullen were competitors in freestyle [[skateboarding]], and Welinder regularly placed 2nd to Mullen's 1st. At a 1983 contest, Mullen (under psychological duress from his father forcing him to soon quit skateboarding, as well as being sick) skated uncharacteristically off and Welinder won.\n\nMullen retired for a year and was soon allowed to return to the scene, overshadowing Welinder and all the other freestylers, but Welinder consistently was the second most popular freestyler in skateboarding. In addition to his freestyle board model, Welinder also had a street model (which was unusual for a freestyler) and this board - with its well-regarded graphic and long nose - was one of the most popular among skateboarders for a few years. This was followed by an unusual, hybrid model of his in 1990 called the \"Nordic Sperm\", which also sold relatively well.\n\nWelinder was featured prominently in the [[Bones Brigade]] videos \"The Bones Brigade Video Show\", \"Future Primitive\", and \"Ban This\". In January, 1992, he left [[Powell Peralta]] to start a new skateboard company, [[Birdhouse Projects]], with fellow team member [[Tony Hawk]] as his partner and main attraction. As Tony Hawk began to achieve superstardom when skateboarding's popularity increased in the mid-1990s, Welinder became a very wealthy man.\n\nIn 2012, Welinder teamed up with longtime skateboard advocate Peter Whitley to author ''Mastering Skateboarding'', which features high-quality full-color photo sequences of all the biggest tricks while spanning techniques and equipment for riders of every level.<ref>{{cite book|last=Welinder|first=Per|title=Mastering Skateboarding|year=2012|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=978-0-7360-9599-0|pages=272}}</ref>\n\n== Appearances in 1980s culture ==\nPer Welinder was a stunt double for some of [[Michael J. Fox]]'s skateboard scenes in the classic 1985 time travel movie ''[[Back to the Future]]''. The year after, he played the part of \"Per\", a Venice freestyler, in the movie ''[[Thrashin']]''.\n\nIn 1986, Welinder was featured in a [[music video]] for [[Blue \u00d6yster Cult]] song \"Dancin' In The Ruins,\" from the album ''[[Club Ninja]]''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0919778}}\n*[http://www.allatalarsvenska.se/film/gangkrig-pa-rullbrada-1986 - Per talking swedish in the movie ''[[Thrashin']]'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Welinder, Per}}\n[[Category:Swedish skateboarders]]\n[[Category:Freestyle skateboarders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Per Welinder\n| image         = Per_Welinder.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = Per Welinder's identity badge in 2016\n| caption       = Welinder in 2016.\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    ={{Birth date and age|1962|04|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Sweden]]\n| occupation    = [[entrepreneur]], [[venture capitalist]], [[brand builder]], [[motivational speaker]], [[professional skateboarder]]\n| salary        =\n| networth      =\n| spouse        =\n| children      =\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = {{URL|twitter.com/perwelinder}}\n| alma_mater    = [[UCLA]] ([[Masters of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])\n| home_town     = [[T\u00e4by]] Sweden\n| net_worth     = \n| known_for     = CEO of [[Blitz Distribution]]; Board Director of [[International Association of Skateboard Companies]]\n}}\n'''Per Nils Welinder''' (born April 17, 1962) is an entrepreneur and a former professional skateboarder. During the 1980s he achieved international fame as a freestyle skater and was a leading member of the elite [[Powell-Peralta]] skate team known as the [[Bones Brigade]]. He had a number of influential video parts with Powell during the 1980s, a series of signature models, and roles in several Hollywood movies. Welinder also has the unique distinction of being the only person to have ever beaten [[Rodney Mullen]] in a professional skate contest.\n\n==Biography==\nWelinder was born in T\u00e4by, just outside [[Stockholm]].  In the 1980s, Welinder and Mullen were competitors in freestyle [[skateboarding]], and Welinder regularly placed 2nd to Mullen's 1st. At a 1983 contest, Mullen (under psychological duress from his father forcing him to soon quit skateboarding, as well as being sick) skated uncharacteristically off and Welinder won.\n\nMullen retired for a year and was soon allowed to return to the scene, overshadowing Welinder and all the other freestylers, but Welinder consistently was the second most popular freestyler in skateboarding. In addition to his freestyle board model, Welinder also had a street model (which was unusual for a freestyler) and this board - with its well-regarded graphic and long nose - was one of the most popular among skateboarders for a few years. This was followed by an unusual, hybrid model of his in 1990 called the \"Nordic Sperm\", which also sold relatively well.\n\nWelinder was featured prominently in the [[Bones Brigade]] videos \"The Bones Brigade Video Show\", \"Future Primitive\", and \"Ban This\". In January, 1992, he left [[Powell Peralta]] to start a new skateboard company, [[Birdhouse Projects]], with fellow team member [[Tony Hawk]] as his partner and main attraction. As Tony Hawk began to achieve superstardom when skateboarding's popularity increased in the mid-1990s, Welinder became a very wealthy man.\n\nIn 2012, Welinder teamed up with longtime skateboard advocate Peter Whitley to author ''Mastering Skateboarding'', which features high-quality full-color photo sequences of all the biggest tricks while spanning techniques and equipment for riders of every level.<ref>{{cite book|last=Welinder|first=Per|title=Mastering Skateboarding|year=2012|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=978-0-7360-9599-0|pages=272}}</ref>\n\n== Appearances in 1980s culture ==\nPer Welinder was a stunt double for some of [[Michael J. Fox]]'s skateboard scenes in the classic 1985 time travel movie ''[[Back to the Future]]''. The year after, he played the part of \"Per\", a Venice freestyler, in the movie ''[[Thrashin']]''.\n\nIn 1986, Welinder was featured in a [[music video]] for [[Blue \u00d6yster Cult]] song \"Dancin' In The Ruins,\" from the album [[Club Ninja]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0919778}}\n*[http://www.allatalarsvenska.se/film/gangkrig-pa-rullbrada-1986 - Per talking swedish in the movie ''[[Thrashin']]'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Welinder, Per}}\n[[Category:Swedish skateboarders]]\n[[Category:Freestyle skateboarders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "italics, fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Per_Welinder"}
{"title_page": "Karala, Delhi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Karala \n| official_name                   = \n| native_name                     = \n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Neighbourhoods of Delhi|Neighbourhood]]\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Delhi\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Delhi, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|28.738|N|77.0392|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Delhi]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[North West Delhi]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Metro\n| subdivision_name3               = \n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = \n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = \n| demographics1_title1            = \n| demographics1_info1             = \n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 110081\n| registration_plate              = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| blank2_name_sec1                = Civic agency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = North Delhi Municipal Corporation \n}}\n\n'''Karala''' is a village in [[North West Delhi]], [[India]]. It is located on the main Kanjhawla road.\n\n==Demographics==\nKarala is the second largest village of Delhi. The main gotra of the people in Karala is Mathur (Jaat)(Matyasar) and others. they are permanent domicile of the area and Delhi too.\n\n==How to reach==\nThe Karala village (https://www.facebook.com/Karalavillage/)  is almost 5&nbsp;km far from mundka railway station, metro station,Distance between Rithala Metro Station and Karala is 10 kms or 6.2 miles or 5.4 nautical miles and almost 7&nbsp;km far from ghewra village railways station.you can easily reach to Karala Village by getting bus no 114, 174 ,921,247, 182,972A,741,962A,962.it is very good place.\n\n== Geography ==\n\nThe village has now been merged with [[Rohini, Delhi|Rohini]] Sector 37,Sector 38,Sector 39 and others.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} Nearby villages are Kanjhawala, Majri, Rani Khera, sultanpur dabas and Begumpur. karala has its own water tank. karala village have its own Sanskrit college the one of the oldest Sanskrit pathshala since the english time. the one of the famous shaheed bhagat singh park situated in the middle of the village called bazar panna the ancient place where all the trade union meeting held. The great Radha Krishna mandir situated in \"Bazar panna\". the temple is the symbol of hindu worship towards lord krishna. The village also has a big stadium with a football playground.The song of famous movie \"Rockstar\" - \"Jo bhi main\" was shoot in the same stadium on 14 December 2010.\n\n== Landmarks ==\n\nThere is a big temple in the town known as Dada Mandu (https://www.facebook.com/Jaidadamandu/) used for worship by the people of Karala and Majri. There is also a big pond adjacent to the temple and an ancient Lord Shiv Mandir. The village also has a big stadium with a football playground. There is also a park named as \"Shaheed Bhagat Singh Park\". karala has also two teams of football which is KFC(Karala Football Club). It has two schools one is primary and another is secondory & sr. Secondary which has two shifts one for girls and evening for boys, one despensary. Karala contains many small new settlements namely Shiv Vihar, AnandPurDham, Rama Vihar etc.\n\n== Administration ==\n\nVillage karala comes under the sdm office and police station of kanjhawla area. It's all judicial activities comes under SDM Saraswati Vihar. All the law and order situation fall under the area of Kanjhawala police station.  The councillor seat no 35 come under karala administration. karala is the head of all the 17 village pardhan. At present Choudhary Samunder is the current pardhan of karala village with 17 village. Karala have 6 chopal including all communities.\n\nThe prominent personality of this village is Sh. Sidharth Mathur, who is a Judge in Delhi. He cleared the judiciary examination in the young age of 26. He is now posted at Delhi High Court as Joint Registrar. \n\n{{coord missing|Delhi}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in North West Delhi district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Karala \n| official_name                   = \n| native_name                     = \n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name      