{"title_page": "Taylor Kitsch", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian actor and model}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Taylor Kitsch\n| alt = \n| image = Taylor Kitsch, 2012.jpg\n| caption = Kitsch in April 2012\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|04|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]], Canadappppppppppppp\n| residence  = [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor, model\n| yearsactive = 2006\u2013present\n}}\n'''Taylor Kitsch''' (born April 8, 1981) is a Canadian actor and model. He is best known for his work in portraying [[Tim Riggins]] in the [[NBC]]fart  series ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2006\u20132011). He has also worked in films such as ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'' (2fart 009), ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'' (2012), ''[[John Carter (film)|John Carter]]'' (2012), ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'' (2012), and ''[[Lone Survivor (film)|Lone Survivor]]'' (2013).\n\nKitsch also starred in the second season of the [[HBO]] series ''[[True Detective]]'' as Paul Woodrugh, appeared in the television film ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]'' (2014) as Bruce Niles, and portrayed [[David Koresh]] in the miniseries ''[[Waco (miniseries)|Waco]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nKitsch was born in [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]]. His mother, Susan (Green), worked for the BC Liquor Board, while his father, Drew Kitsch, worked in construction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/27222 |title='Friday Night Lights' star looks back ... and ahead |publisher=ScrippsNews |date=October 2, 2007 |accessdate=January 8, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407064547/http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/27222 |archivedate=April 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor Kitsch: the next action hero|url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2012/03/02/the-next-action-hero/|work=[[Maclean's]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|author=Brian D. Johnson|date=March 2, 2012}}</ref> His parents separated when he was one, and he and his two older brothers, Brody<ref name=NYTimes-Brody-2006>{{cite news|last1=Hoinski|first1=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/17/fashion/17nite.html|title=A Night Out With: Texas Forever (via Canada)|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 9, 2015|date=December 17, 2006}}</ref> and Daman, were raised by their mother in a mobile home park.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a28918/taylor-kitsch-profile-true-detective/ |title=Taylor Kitsch Lives Up to Our Fantasies |publisher=Elle.com |date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outsideonline.com/photo-galleries/Taylor-Kitsch.html |title=Taylor Kitsch Photo Gallery &#124; Outside Magazine's Featured Photo Galleries |publisher=OutsideOnline.com |date= |accessdate=January 8, 2012}}</ref> He also has two younger maternal half-sisters. Kitsch lived in [[Port Moody]] and [[Anmore]].<ref name=\"davidkarp\">{{cite web|last1=Karp|first1=David|title=Friday Night Lightd star has B.C. roots|url=http://davidkarp.ca/Arts_files/taylor%20kitsch.pdf|website=[[The Martlet]] Online|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=January 13, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702123208/http://davidkarp.ca/Arts_files/taylor%20kitsch.pdf|archivedate=July 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He attended [[Gleneagle Secondary School]] in [[Coquitlam]].<ref>The Georgia Straight: [https://www.straight.com/movies/john-carters-taylor-kitsch-taking-mars-and-hollywood John Carter's Taylor Kitsch is taking Mars and Hollywood] Retrieved on March 7, 2012</ref> Kitsch started playing ice hockey at age three,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title=\u2018Lone Survivor\u2019 Taylor Kitsch\u2019s Journey From Homelessness to Hollywood Stardom|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/12/18/lone-survivor-taylor-kitsch-s-journey-from-homelessness-to-hollywood-stardom.html|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=December 18, 2013}}</ref> and played [[junior ice hockey]] for the [[Langley Hornets]] in the [[British Columbia Hockey League]], before a knee injury ended his career in 2002.<ref>{{Citation|last=CBC|title=George Tonight: Taylor Kitsch On Hockey And Being Homeless {{!}} George Stroumboulopoulos Tonight {{!}} CBC|date=2011-01-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66dbkyww3ec|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> Following his injury, Kitsch took nutrition and economics courses at the [[University of Lethbridge]] for a year and lived with his brother.<ref name=\"davidkarp\"/>\n\n==Career==\nKitsch moved to [[New York City]] in 2002, after receiving an opportunity to pursue modeling with [[IMG (business)|IMG]]; he studied acting there as well, and became a nutritionist and [[personal trainer]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Taylor Kitsch Gives Dietary Help|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/taylor-kitsch-gives-dietary-help_1299117|magazine=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=March 3, 2012}}</ref> For a time in New York he was [[homeless]] and took to sleeping on subway trains in the middle of the night.<ref name=\"thenational1\">{{cite news|last=Mottram|first=James|title=Taylor Kitsch's career hits a crest|url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/film/taylor-kitschs-career-hits-a-crest|newspaper=thenational.ae|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=April 19, 2012}}</ref> In 2004, he relocated to [[Los Angeles]], where he modeled for [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]] and [[Abercrombie & Fitch]].<ref name=\"thenational1\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor Kitsch biography and filmography|url=http://www.tribute.ca/people/taylor-kitsch/17390/|publisher=tribute.ca|accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> He also appeared in the limited edition coffee table book ''About Face'' by celebrity photographer John Russo.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEW-RELEASES - About Face|url=http://www.pixiepressworldwide.com/NEW-RELEASES.aspx|publisher=Pixie Press Worldwide|accessdate=April 19, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418001837/http://www.pixiepressworldwide.com/NEW-RELEASES.aspx|archivedate=April 18, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Kitsch was cast in his breakout role on the [[NBC]] sports teen drama television series ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'', based on [[Peter Berg]]'s 2004 film [[Friday Night Lights (film)|of the same name]] and set in the fictional town of Dillon, Texas. For five seasons, Kitsch portrayed the role of [[Tim Riggins]], a high school student who is the [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]]/[[running back]] of the Dillon Panthers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/characters/tim-riggins|title=Tim Riggins profile|publisher=TV Fanatic|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref> The series premiered in October 2006 to universal critical acclaim from critics and over 7.7 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv|title=TV Reviews, Articles, Clips and more|website=Metacritic|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref> Kitsch has ruled out reprising his role in a potential film sequel to the television series.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ryan Lambie |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/18985/peter-berg-interview-directing-battleship-filming-at-sea-kevin-costner-ilm-effects-and-more|title=Peter Berg interview: directing Battleship, filming at sea, Kevin Costner, ILM effects and more|publisher=Den of Geek|date=April 2, 2012|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref> He played Pogue Parry  in ''[[The Covenant (film)|The Covenant]]'', alongside [[Steven Strait]], [[Sebastian Stan]], [[Laura Ramsey]], [[Toby Hemingway]], [[Jessica Lucas]] and [[Chace Crawford]]. In February 2008, he signed on to play [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]] in the [[X-Men]] franchise spinoff ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'', released in May 2009. Of the fan-favorite character Gambit, Kitsch states, \"I knew of him, but I didn't know the following he had. I'm sure I'm still going to be exposed to that. I love the character, I love the powers, and I love what they did with him. I didn't know that much, but in my experience, it was a blessing to go in and create my take on him. I'm excited for it, to say the least.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=The MovieWeb Team |url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/NEh0tojn6wmWki |title=Taylor Kitsch on Being Gambit in X-Men Origins: Wolverine |publisher=MovieWeb.com |date=October 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kitsch starred in [[Steven Silver (film director)|Steven Silver]]'s ''[[The Bang Bang Club (film)|The Bang Bang Club]]'', an [[historical drama]] set in [[South Africa]] which documents the final bloody days of the [[apartheid]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Yamato|first=Jen|title=Taylor Kitsch on The Bang Bang Club, Honoring Fallen War Photographers, and Battleship|url=http://movieline.com/2011/04/22/taylor-kitsch-on-doing-justice-to-fallen-photojournalists-in-the-bang-bang-club/|work=[[Movieline]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=April 22, 2011}}</ref> He had to lose 35 pounds in two months to play the role of photojournalist [[Kevin Carter]], alongside [[Ryan Phillippe]] and [[Malin \u00c5kerman]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Logan|title=Taylor Kitsch on John Carter of Mars, Battleship, and Why Bang Bang Club Forced Him to Seek Psychiatric Help|url=http://www.vulture.com/2011/04/taylor_kitsch_tk.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=April 18, 2011}}</ref> In November 2010, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' named Kitsch as one of the young male actors who are \"pushing \u2013 or being pushed\" into taking over Hollywood as the new \"A-List\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cover-hollywood-reporter-43374|title=See the Cover of the New Hollywood Reporter|last=THR staff|date=November 9, 2010|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/hollywoods-list-redefined-44771|title=Hollywood's A-List Redefined|last=Lauren Schutte|first=Emily Blank|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011|date=November 15, 2010}}</ref> In the 2012 [[Disney]] film ''[[John Carter (film)|John Carter]]'', based on [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]]'s fantasy novel ''[[A Princess of Mars]]'', he played the title character, a Confederate soldier who is transported to Mars. Despite the film's failure at the box office, Kitsch said, \"I'm very proud of ''John Carter''. Box office doesn't validate me as a person, or as an actor.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Wigler|first=Josh|title='John Carter' Wasn't A Failure, Taylor Kitsch Says|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2012/04/03/john-carter-failure-taylor-kitsch|publisher=MTV|accessdate=April 15, 2012|date=March 4, 2012}}</ref> In May 2012, Kitsch starred in [[Peter Berg]]'s ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'', based on [[Battleship (game)|Hasbro's toy game]], as Lieutenant Alex Hopper.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jeff|last=Leins|title=Taylor Kitsch to Star in 'Battleship'|work=News in Film|date=June 12, 2009|url=http://www.newsinfilm.com/2010/04/08/taylor-kitsch-to-star-in-battleship|accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref> It, too, failed at the box office. The film marked his reunion with Berg and former ''Friday Night Lights'' co-star, [[Jesse Plemons]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Radish|first=Christina|title=Brooklyn Decker and Director Peter Berg Talk BATTLESHIP, Naval Warfare and the Design of the Aliens at WonderCon|url=http://collider.com/brooklyn-decker-peter-berg-battleship-interview/153633/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=April 15, 2012|date=March 19, 2012}}</ref> In July 2012, he starred in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'', with [[Blake Lively]], [[Salma Hayek]] and [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson]]. ''[[HitFix]]''{{'s}} film critic [[Drew McWeeny]] wrote positively of Kitsch's bond with Johnson which he described as \"not only credible but lived in and authentic throughout the film\". McWeeny wrote that Kitsch was used the right way in this film with an ensemble cast that pushed him or challenged him in scenes which resulted in his playing them with appropriate intensity.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny|first=Drew|title=Review: Oliver Stone turns Aaron Johnson, Taylor Kitsch, and Blake Lively into 'Savages'|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-oliver-stone-turns-aaron-johnson-taylor-kitsch-and-blake-lively-into-savages|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=August 24, 2012|date=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Kitsch starred in ''[[The Grand Seduction]]'', remake of [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Pouliot]]'s French-Canadian ''La Grande S\u00e9duction'' (2003) directed by [[Don McKellar]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Brendan Gleeson, Taylor Kitsch Find \u2018The Grand Seduction\u2019|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/brendan-gleeson-taylor-kitsch-find-the-grand-seduction/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]]|accessdate=August 25, 2012|date=July 30, 2012}}</ref> and another Peter Berg film, ''[[Lone Survivor (film)|Lone Survivor]]'', based on [[Marcus Luttrell]]'s [[Lone Survivor (book)|book]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Universal, Peter Berg Plot January Start For Navy SEAL Saga 'Lone Survivor'|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/05/universal-peter-berg-plot-january-start-for-navy-seal-saga-lone-survivor|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=PMC|accessdate=August 25, 2012|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref> He plays alongside [[Jim Parsons]], [[Julia Roberts]] and [[Mark Ruffalo]] in [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]'s ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]'', which aired on HBO on May 25, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Jim Parsons, Taylor Kitsch Join HBO's Ryan Murphy-directed movie, 'The Normal Heart'|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/jim-parsons-taylor-kitsch-join-hbos-ryan-murphy-directed-movie-the-normal-heart|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 9, 2013|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref> Kitsch was in negotiations for the lead role in [[The Raid: Redemption#American remake|the American remake of ''The Raid'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/taylor-kitsch-offered-lead-in-the-raid-remake-exclusive/|title=Taylor Kitsch Offered Lead in \u2018The Raid\u2019 Remake (Exclusive)|last=Sneider |first=Jeff|work=The Wrap|date=August 4, 2014|accessdate=August 4, 2014}}</ref> Kitsch starred in the sophomore season of ''[[True Detective]]'', opposite [[Vince Vaughn]], [[Rachel McAdams]], and [[Colin Farrell]]. Kitsch will write, direct and star in the drama Pieces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/taylor-kitsch-pieces-directorial-debut-peter-berg-lone-survivor-emmett-furla-oasis-1201724489/|title=\u2018Lone Survivor\u2019s Taylor Kitsch To Star In And Direct His Thriller Script \u2018Pieces\u2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Fleming, Jr|first=Mike|date=March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Kitsch starred in ''[[American Assassin]]'', where he plays the main villain, and ''[[Only the Brave (2017 film)|Only the Brave]]''. In 2018, he played the part of cult leader [[David Koresh]] in the Paramount Channel miniseries ''[[Waco (miniseries)|Waco]]''.\nIn 2019 Kitsch starred in \u201c21 Bridges\u201d with Chadwick Bozeman and Sienna Miller.\n\n==Personal life==\nKitsch purchased 3.64 acres of land on [[Lake Austin]], Texas in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2012/dirt/real-estalker/canadian-taylor-kitsch-buys-bare-land-in-texas-1201233311/|title=Canadian Taylor Kitsch Buys Bare Land in Texas|author=Mark David|work=Variety}}</ref> and began building a house there in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://statesmanshots.blog.statesman.com/2015/12/17/statesman-shots-91-taylor-kitsch-on-african-childrens-choir-and-post-fnl-life/|title=Statesman Shots #91: Taylor Kitsch on African Children\u2019s Choir and post-\u2018FNL\u2019 life|publisher=Statesman Shots}}</ref> Kitsch currently resides in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/taylor-kitsch-waco-profile|title=Taylor Kitsch on 'Waco', Tim Riggins, and the Movie That Nearly Destroyed His Career|date=January 25, 2018|first=Peele|last=Anna|website=GQ}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[John Tucker Must Die]]''\n| Justin\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Snakes on a Plane]]''\n| Kyle \"Crocodile\" Cho\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Covenant (film)|The Covenant]]''\n| Pogue Parry\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Gospel Hill]]''\n| Joel Herrod\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]''\n| [[Gambit (comics)|Remy LeBeau / Gambit]]\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Bang Bang Club (film)|The Bang Bang Club]]''\n| [[Kevin Carter]] \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[John Carter (film)|John Carter]]''\n| [[John Carter of Mars|John Carter]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]''\n| Lt. Alex Hopper\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''\n| Chon\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Lone Survivor (film)|Lone Survivor]]''\n| [[Michael P. Murphy]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Grand Seduction]]''\n| Dr. Paul Lewis\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Bling (film)|Bling]]''\n| Sam<br>(voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[American Assassin]]''\n| Ghost\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Only the Brave (2017 film)|Only the Brave]]''\n| Christopher MacKenzie\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[21 Bridges]]''\n|Ray Jackson \n| \n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Godiva's]]''\n| Colm\n| Episode: \"Flipping Switches\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Kyle XY]]''\n| Male Camper\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 2006\u20132011\n| ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]''\n| [[Tim Riggins]]\n| 68 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]''\n| Bruce Niles\n| [[Television film]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[True Detective]]\n| Paul Woodrugh\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Waco (miniseries)|Waco]]''\n| [[David Koresh]]\n| [[Miniseries]]<br />6 episodes<br>Also executive producer\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2007\n| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n|Choice TV: Breakout\n| ''Friday Night Lights''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| Teen Choice Awards\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Actor Drama|Choice TV Actor: Drama]]\n| ''Friday Night Lights''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Teen Choice Awards\n|Choice Movie Fresh Face Male\n| ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2010\n|[[People's Choice Awards]]\n|Favorite On-Screen Team\n| ''X-Men Origins: Wolverine''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Genie Awards]]\n|[[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Performance by an Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n|''The Bang Bang Club''\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[National Association of Theatre Owners#CinemaCon Awards 2012|CinemaCon Awards]]\n| Male Star of Tomorrow \n| Himself\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| 2014\n| Online Film & Television Association Awards\n| Best Supporting Actor in a Motion Picture or Miniseries\n|''The Normal Heart''\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Rebecca|title=Taylor Kitsch is the Male Star of Tomorrow|url=http://movies.about.com/b/2012/04/12/taylor-kitsch-is-the-male-star-of-tomorrow.htm|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=August 8, 2013|date=April 12, 2012}}</ref> \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|2018237}}\n* {{icehockeystats|elite=265284}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kitsch, Taylor}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey forwards]]\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male models]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kelowna]]\n[[Category:People from Coquitlam]]\n[[Category:University of Lethbridge alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian actor and model}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Taylor Kitsch\n| alt = \n| image = Taylor Kitsch, 2012.jpg\n| caption = Kitsch in April 2012\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|04|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| residence  = [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor, model\n| yearsactive = 2006\u2013present\n}}\n'''Taylor Kitsch''' (born April 8, 1981) is a Canadian actor and model. He is best known for his work in portraying [[Tim Riggins]] in the [[NBC]] television series ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2006\u20132011). He has also worked in films such as ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'' (2009), ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'' (2012), ''[[John Carter (film)|John Carter]]'' (2012), ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'' (2012), and ''[[Lone Survivor (film)|Lone Survivor]]'' (2013).\n\nKitsch also starred in the second season of the [[HBO]] series ''[[True Detective]]'' as Paul Woodrugh, appeared in the television film ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]'' (2014) as Bruce Niles, and portrayed [[David Koresh]] in the miniseries ''[[Waco (miniseries)|Waco]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nKitsch was born in [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]]. His mother, Susan (Green), worked for the BC Liquor Board, while his father, Drew Kitsch, worked in construction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/27222 |title='Friday Night Lights' star looks back ... and ahead |publisher=ScrippsNews |date=October 2, 2007 |accessdate=January 8, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407064547/http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/27222 |archivedate=April 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor Kitsch: the next action hero|url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2012/03/02/the-next-action-hero/|work=[[Maclean's]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|author=Brian D. Johnson|date=March 2, 2012}}</ref> His parents separated when he was one, and he and his two older brothers, Brody<ref name=NYTimes-Brody-2006>{{cite news|last1=Hoinski|first1=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/17/fashion/17nite.html|title=A Night Out With: Texas Forever (via Canada)|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=August 9, 2015|date=December 17, 2006}}</ref> and Daman, were raised by their mother in a mobile home park.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Alyssa |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a28918/taylor-kitsch-profile-true-detective/ |title=Taylor Kitsch Lives Up to Our Fantasies |publisher=Elle.com |date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outsideonline.com/photo-galleries/Taylor-Kitsch.html |title=Taylor Kitsch Photo Gallery &#124; Outside Magazine's Featured Photo Galleries |publisher=OutsideOnline.com |date= |accessdate=January 8, 2012}}</ref> He also has two younger maternal half-sisters. Kitsch lived in [[Port Moody]] and [[Anmore]].<ref name=\"davidkarp\">{{cite web|last1=Karp|first1=David|title=Friday Night Lightd star has B.C. roots|url=http://davidkarp.ca/Arts_files/taylor%20kitsch.pdf|website=[[The Martlet]] Online|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=January 13, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702123208/http://davidkarp.ca/Arts_files/taylor%20kitsch.pdf|archivedate=July 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He attended [[Gleneagle Secondary School]] in [[Coquitlam]].<ref>The Georgia Straight: [https://www.straight.com/movies/john-carters-taylor-kitsch-taking-mars-and-hollywood John Carter's Taylor Kitsch is taking Mars and Hollywood] Retrieved on March 7, 2012</ref> Kitsch started playing ice hockey at age three,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title=\u2018Lone Survivor\u2019 Taylor Kitsch\u2019s Journey From Homelessness to Hollywood Stardom|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/12/18/lone-survivor-taylor-kitsch-s-journey-from-homelessness-to-hollywood-stardom.html|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=August 10, 2015|date=December 18, 2013}}</ref> and played [[junior ice hockey]] for the [[Langley Hornets]] in the [[British Columbia Hockey League]], before a knee injury ended his career in 2002.<ref>{{Citation|last=CBC|title=George Tonight: Taylor Kitsch On Hockey And Being Homeless {{!}} George Stroumboulopoulos Tonight {{!}} CBC|date=2011-01-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66dbkyww3ec|access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> Following his injury, Kitsch took nutrition and economics courses at the [[University of Lethbridge]] for a year and lived with his brother.<ref name=\"davidkarp\"/>\n\n==Career==\nKitsch moved to [[New York City]] in 2002, after receiving an opportunity to pursue modeling with [[IMG (business)|IMG]]; he studied acting there as well, and became a nutritionist and [[personal trainer]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Taylor Kitsch Gives Dietary Help|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/taylor-kitsch-gives-dietary-help_1299117|magazine=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=March 3, 2012}}</ref> For a time in New York he was [[homeless]] and took to sleeping on subway trains in the middle of the night.<ref name=\"thenational1\">{{cite news|last=Mottram|first=James|title=Taylor Kitsch's career hits a crest|url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/film/taylor-kitschs-career-hits-a-crest|newspaper=thenational.ae|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=April 19, 2012}}</ref> In 2004, he relocated to [[Los Angeles]], where he modeled for [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]] and [[Abercrombie & Fitch]].<ref name=\"thenational1\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Taylor Kitsch biography and filmography|url=http://www.tribute.ca/people/taylor-kitsch/17390/|publisher=tribute.ca|accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref> He also appeared in the limited edition coffee table book ''About Face'' by celebrity photographer John Russo.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEW-RELEASES - About Face|url=http://www.pixiepressworldwide.com/NEW-RELEASES.aspx|publisher=Pixie Press Worldwide|accessdate=April 19, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418001837/http://www.pixiepressworldwide.com/NEW-RELEASES.aspx|archivedate=April 18, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Kitsch was cast in his breakout role on the [[NBC]] sports teen drama television series ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'', based on [[Peter Berg]]'s 2004 film [[Friday Night Lights (film)|of the same name]] and set in the fictional town of Dillon, Texas. For five seasons, Kitsch portrayed the role of [[Tim Riggins]], a high school student who is the [[Fullback (American football)|fullback]]/[[running back]] of the Dillon Panthers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/characters/tim-riggins|title=Tim Riggins profile|publisher=TV Fanatic|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref> The series premiered in October 2006 to universal critical acclaim from critics and over 7.7 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv|title=TV Reviews, Articles, Clips and more|website=Metacritic|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref> Kitsch has ruled out reprising his role in a potential film sequel to the television series.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ryan Lambie |url=http://www.denofgeek.com/movies/18985/peter-berg-interview-directing-battleship-filming-at-sea-kevin-costner-ilm-effects-and-more|title=Peter Berg interview: directing Battleship, filming at sea, Kevin Costner, ILM effects and more|publisher=Den of Geek|date=April 2, 2012|accessdate=September 25, 2012}}</ref> He played Pogue Parry  in ''[[The Covenant (film)|The Covenant]]'', alongside [[Steven Strait]], [[Sebastian Stan]], [[Laura Ramsey]], [[Toby Hemingway]], [[Jessica Lucas]] and [[Chace Crawford]]. In February 2008, he signed on to play [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]] in the [[X-Men]] franchise spinoff ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'', released in May 2009. Of the fan-favorite character Gambit, Kitsch states, \"I knew of him, but I didn't know the following he had. I'm sure I'm still going to be exposed to that. I love the character, I love the powers, and I love what they did with him. I didn't know that much, but in my experience, it was a blessing to go in and create my take on him. I'm excited for it, to say the least.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=The MovieWeb Team |url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/NEh0tojn6wmWki |title=Taylor Kitsch on Being Gambit in X-Men Origins: Wolverine |publisher=MovieWeb.com |date=October 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kitsch starred in [[Steven Silver (film director)|Steven Silver]]'s ''[[The Bang Bang Club (film)|The Bang Bang Club]]'', an [[historical drama]] set in [[South Africa]] which documents the final bloody days of the [[apartheid]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Yamato|first=Jen|title=Taylor Kitsch on The Bang Bang Club, Honoring Fallen War Photographers, and Battleship|url=http://movieline.com/2011/04/22/taylor-kitsch-on-doing-justice-to-fallen-photojournalists-in-the-bang-bang-club/|work=[[Movieline]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=April 22, 2011}}</ref> He had to lose 35 pounds in two months to play the role of photojournalist [[Kevin Carter]], alongside [[Ryan Phillippe]] and [[Malin \u00c5kerman]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Logan|title=Taylor Kitsch on John Carter of Mars, Battleship, and Why Bang Bang Club Forced Him to Seek Psychiatric Help|url=http://www.vulture.com/2011/04/taylor_kitsch_tk.html|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=April 19, 2012|date=April 18, 2011}}</ref> In November 2010, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' named Kitsch as one of the young male actors who are \"pushing \u2013 or being pushed\" into taking over Hollywood as the new \"A-List\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cover-hollywood-reporter-43374|title=See the Cover of the New Hollywood Reporter|last=THR staff|date=November 9, 2010|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/hollywoods-list-redefined-44771|title=Hollywood's A-List Redefined|last=Lauren Schutte|first=Emily Blank|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=April 13, 2011|date=November 15, 2010}}</ref> In the 2012 [[Disney]] film ''[[John Carter (film)|John Carter]]'', based on [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]]'s fantasy novel ''[[A Princess of Mars]]'', he played the title character, a Confederate soldier who is transported to Mars. Despite the film's failure at the box office, Kitsch said, \"I'm very proud of ''John Carter''. Box office doesn't validate me as a person, or as an actor.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Wigler|first=Josh|title='John Carter' Wasn't A Failure, Taylor Kitsch Says|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2012/04/03/john-carter-failure-taylor-kitsch|publisher=MTV|accessdate=April 15, 2012|date=March 4, 2012}}</ref> In May 2012, Kitsch starred in [[Peter Berg]]'s ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]'', based on [[Battleship (game)|Hasbro's toy game]], as Lieutenant Alex Hopper.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jeff|last=Leins|title=Taylor Kitsch to Star in 'Battleship'|work=News in Film|date=June 12, 2009|url=http://www.newsinfilm.com/2010/04/08/taylor-kitsch-to-star-in-battleship|accessdate=April 8, 2010}}</ref> It, too, failed at the box office. The film marked his reunion with Berg and former ''Friday Night Lights'' co-star, [[Jesse Plemons]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Radish|first=Christina|title=Brooklyn Decker and Director Peter Berg Talk BATTLESHIP, Naval Warfare and the Design of the Aliens at WonderCon|url=http://collider.com/brooklyn-decker-peter-berg-battleship-interview/153633/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=April 15, 2012|date=March 19, 2012}}</ref> In July 2012, he starred in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'', with [[Blake Lively]], [[Salma Hayek]] and [[Aaron Taylor-Johnson]]. ''[[HitFix]]''{{'s}} film critic [[Drew McWeeny]] wrote positively of Kitsch's bond with Johnson which he described as \"not only credible but lived in and authentic throughout the film\". McWeeny wrote that Kitsch was used the right way in this film with an ensemble cast that pushed him or challenged him in scenes which resulted in his playing them with appropriate intensity.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny|first=Drew|title=Review: Oliver Stone turns Aaron Johnson, Taylor Kitsch, and Blake Lively into 'Savages'|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-oliver-stone-turns-aaron-johnson-taylor-kitsch-and-blake-lively-into-savages|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=August 24, 2012|date=June 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Kitsch starred in ''[[The Grand Seduction]]'', remake of [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Pouliot]]'s French-Canadian ''La Grande S\u00e9duction'' (2003) directed by [[Don McKellar]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Brendan Gleeson, Taylor Kitsch Find \u2018The Grand Seduction\u2019|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/brendan-gleeson-taylor-kitsch-find-the-grand-seduction/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]]|accessdate=August 25, 2012|date=July 30, 2012}}</ref> and another Peter Berg film, ''[[Lone Survivor (film)|Lone Survivor]]'', based on [[Marcus Luttrell]]'s [[Lone Survivor (book)|book]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike|title=Universal, Peter Berg Plot January Start For Navy SEAL Saga 'Lone Survivor'|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/05/universal-peter-berg-plot-january-start-for-navy-seal-saga-lone-survivor|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=PMC|accessdate=August 25, 2012|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref> He plays alongside [[Jim Parsons]], [[Julia Roberts]] and [[Mark Ruffalo]] in [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]'s ''[[The Normal Heart (film)|The Normal Heart]]'', which aired on HBO on May 25, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Jim Parsons, Taylor Kitsch Join HBO's Ryan Murphy-directed movie, 'The Normal Heart'|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/jim-parsons-taylor-kitsch-join-hbos-ryan-murphy-directed-movie-the-normal-heart|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 9, 2013|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref> Kitsch was in negotiations for the lead role in [[The Raid: Redemption#American remake|the American remake of ''The Raid'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/taylor-kitsch-offered-lead-in-the-raid-remake-exclusive/|title=Taylor Kitsch Offered Lead in \u2018The Raid\u2019 Remake (Exclusive)|last=Sneider |first=Jeff|work=The Wrap|date=August 4, 2014|accessdate=August 4, 2014}}</ref> Kitsch starred in the sophomore season of ''[[True Detective]]'', opposite [[Vince Vaughn]], [[Rachel McAdams]], and [[Colin Farrell]]. Kitsch will write, direct and star in the drama Pieces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/taylor-kitsch-pieces-directorial-debut-peter-berg-lone-survivor-emmett-furla-oasis-1201724489/|title=\u2018Lone Survivor\u2019s Taylor Kitsch To Star In And Direct His Thriller Script \u2018Pieces\u2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Fleming, Jr|first=Mike|date=March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Kitsch starred in ''[[American Assassin]]'', where he plays the main villain, and ''[[Only the Brave (2017 film)|Only the Brave]]''. In 2018, he played the part of cult leader [[David Koresh]] in the Paramount Channel miniseries ''[[Waco (miniseries)|Waco]]''.\nIn 2019 Kitsch starred in \u201c21 Bridges\u201d with Chadwick Bozeman and Sienna Miller.\n\n==Personal life==\nKitsch purchased 3.64 acres of land on [[Lake Austin]], Texas in 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2012/dirt/real-estalker/canadian-taylor-kitsch-buys-bare-land-in-texas-1201233311/|title=Canadian Taylor Kitsch Buys Bare Land in Texas|author=Mark David|work=Variety}}</ref> and began building a house there in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://statesmanshots.blog.statesman.com/2015/12/17/statesman-shots-91-taylor-kitsch-on-african-childrens-choir-and-post-fnl-life/|title=Statesman Shots #91: Taylor Kitsch on African Children\u2019s Choir and post-\u2018FNL\u2019 life|publisher=Statesman Shots}}</ref> Kitsch currently resides in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/taylor-kitsch-waco-profile|title=Taylor Kitsch on 'Waco', Tim Riggins, and the Movie That Nearly Destroyed His Career|date=January 25, 2018|first=Peele|last=Anna|website=GQ}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[John Tucker Must Die]]''\n| Justin\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Snakes on a Plane]]''\n| Kyle \"Crocodile\" Cho\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Covenant (film)|The Covenant]]''\n| Pogue Parry\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Gospel Hill]]''\n| Joel Herrod\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]''\n| [[Gambit (comics)|Remy LeBeau / Gambit]]\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Bang Bang Club (film)|The Bang Bang Club]]''\n| [[Kevin Carter]] \n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[John Carter (film)|John Carter]]''\n| [[John Carter of Mars|John Carter]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Battleship (film)|Battleship]]''\n| Lt. Alex Hopper\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''\n| Chon\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Lone Survivor (film)|Lone Survivor]]''\n| [[Michael P. Murphy]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Grand Seduction]]''\n| Dr. Paul Lewis\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Bling (film)|Bling]]''\n| Sam<br>(voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[American Assassin]]''\n| Ghost\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Only the Brave (2017 film)|Only the Brave]]''\n| Christopher MacKenzie\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[21 Bridges]]''\n|Ray Jackson \n| \n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Godiva's]]''\n| Colm\n| Episode: \"Flipping Switches\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Kyle XY]]''\n| Male Camper\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 2006\u20132011\n| '